Troubleshooting Tips
SNMP Service Won't Start:

Check configuration syntax: sudo snmpd -Lf /dev/null -c /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf
Verify user creation directives are properly formatted
Ensure no duplicate user definitions exist
NTP Not Synchronizing:

Check firewall rules: sudo ufw status
Verify network connectivity to pool servers: ping 0.pool.ntp.org
Review NTP logs: sudo journalctl -u ntp -n 50
Python Scripts Fail:

Verify Python 3 is installed: python3 --version
Install missing modules: pip3 install pysnmp
Check file permissions: chmod +x script.py
Run with sudo if accessing system files
Conclusion
This lab provided hands-on experience auditing and hardening critical network infrastructure services. Students learned to identify SNMPv3 vulnerabilities including weak authentication protocols (MD5), insufficient encryption (DES), and overly permissive access controls. The NTP monitoring implementation demonstrated detection of time synchronization attacks, peer reachability issues, and amplification risks.

Key takeaways include the importance of strong cryptographic protocols (SHA-256, AES-256), principle of least privilege in access control, and continuous monitoring for security anomalies. The automation scripts developed enable repeatable security assessments and consistent hardening across infrastructure deployments.

These skills are essential for securing network management and time synchronization services in production environments, preventing common attack vectors like SNMP enumeration and NTP amplification DDoS attacks.
